newsitem.title: UK: Med oil products end mostly up, helped by futures.
newsitem.headline: Med oil products end mostly up, helped by futures.

text.p: Mediterranean oil products were mostly higher on Thursday tracking recent gains in crude and products futures, traders said.
Gasoline edged higher tracking NWE prices and a firm crude market, but traders said premium unleaded was balanced while lower octane grades were well supplies.
"Essentially there is no buying for November," said one trader. "There is more supply of lower octane and no buyers."
He said the arbitrage to the U.S. looked shut but sellers may be forced to look there for buyers.
Naphtha also rose, catching up recent gains in crude. The Med was also seen balanced and traders were awaiting results of the Egyptian tender for 1997, where bids were re-submitted.

Gas oil gained on firmer futures but business was inactive. Discussion was dominated by the announcement of a Turkish tender for 100,000 tonnes of 0.5 percent sulphur for December which traders said would provide direction in an inactive market.

"Sellers are at really high numbers and buyers are saying 'no'. This market is probably overdone but I don't see the sellers coming off until something proves it and their backs are against the wall," one trader said.
Cargoes were offered at cif high quotes +$3/+$2 into Greece with Italians, Romanians and Bulgarians offered variously at cif high quotes +$1/$2.

Low sulphur cracked fuel was firmer with a deal in the north at $128.50 fob NWE while Dec and Nov swaps sold at $129.50 fob. Paper numbers eased $1-2 but the physical remained strong. High freight rates of up to $11 a tonne result from scarce tonnage.
High sulphur cracked fuel oil was steady with a lack of activity.
